courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Develop self-awareness and self-management of one’s own psychological well-being;
2. Apply knowledge and skills to assess strengths and needs of the community, and develop corresponding courses of action;
3. Develop empathy, care and concern, and respect towards people;
4. Evaluate how volunteerism and service learning can bring about positive changes to the community;
5. Reflect on how their own discipline relates to and contributes to the society; and
6. Develop an enhanced sense of civic responsibility to promote greater good in the society.

Knowledge outcomes

* To become familiar with some of the basic concepts and themes of Buddhism;
* To understand Buddhist attitude to and connections with modern society in various historical settings and contemporary contexts;
* To engage in a critical analysis of how Buddhism has accommodated itself with the modernization movements, and been reinvented to make it meaningful and useful to people nowadays;
* To examine in what ways Buddhism transforms traditional and modern society and culture, and vice versa.

Attitude outcomes

* To develop a critical and sympathetic attitude in understanding religious phenomena
* To develop a sensitivity to religious dimension of human life;
* To relate students’ personal growth and everyday life to Buddhist teachings so as to cultivate a constructive outlook on self understanding and interpersonal relationship.
* To enhance students’ understanding of Buddhist ways in promoting healthy lives and well-being for all at all ages.

Skill Outcomes

* Students will be able to develop their key research skills including textual and fieldwork studies and to prepare for advanced studies in religion;
* Students will be able to develop their presentation skills and ability to work collaboratively in a team.

Upon completing the course, the students are expected:

1. To apply their learning experience to the carrying out of community studies;

2. To discover the needs and problems faced by the poor people in China;

3. To recognize the limits and possibilities of the poverty alleviation and development projects;

4. To evaluate poverty alleviation and development strategies of Government and NGOs in China;

5. To develop skills in cross-disciplinary studies, collaboration and teamwork.

courses.course_syllabus:
The major concepts to be covered include: The conceptual distinctions between sex and gender; the multicultural understanding of family, and the concept of globalization.

The major topics to be covered include:
1) the conceptual interconnection between gender and family;
2) cultural and national diversities in understanding of family, its structure and dynamics;
3) the intersection between the public and the private domain as evidenced by close links between unpaid housework and paid employment, the more intricate interrelations between paid household work provided by foreign domestic helper and the family, the tension between parenting and work, and ;
4) the globalized movement towards gender equality as illustrated by global networks and advocacy against domestic violence and sexual harassment, and the global call for family policies that promote gender equality and gender mainstreaming.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Appraise in depth their personal, social, emotional, cognitive and intellectual development in relation to their service- learning experience;

2. Apply the theories and skills they learnt to assess critically on the needs and situations of a vulnerable group, in turn, to plan and identify a series of action for the situations;

3. Appreciate the practices and values of service-learning, altruism, volunteerism and civil engagement in bringing about a care and concern society;

4. Have genuine care and human concern for the vulnerable situations in society;

5. Develop a long-term civil commitment to the well-being and betterment of society;

6. Practise constant self-reflection in order to achieve self-discovery and self-advancement.

courses.course_syllabus:
This course is divided into the following parts. Part 1 deals with the historical and cultural perspectives of treating people with disability. Part 2 focuses on the theoretical and practical frameworks of disability. Part 3 handles the selected types of disability. Part 4 concentrates on professional workers’ roles in serving their clients with special needs. The course is designed to cover the following topics:

- A brief history of the ways different cultures have treated persons with a disability;
- Societal and professional stereotypes towards disability;
- Different theoretical models such as the medical model, the social model, the empowerment model, etc.;
- Selected disabilities such as the developmental disabilities; mental disorders; visual impairment; hearing impairment; persons with psychiatric disability; etc.

- Social services for persons with a disability, and

- The roles of professional workers in working with clients who have a disability and their families.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Students of this course will be able to:

- critically examine the intersection of social inequalities and environmental issues;

- distinguish environmental sustainable development goals that can be achieved through the service learning approach;

- apply conceptual tools to design service-learning projects to mitigate environmental problems;

- identify and evaluate distributional issues related to environmental impact;

- recognise the environmental needs and voices of communities through service experience;

- utilize acquired skills to foster community participation in sustainability-promoting service activities;

- formulate collaborative plan with teammates to solve social-environmental issues;

- reflect critically on their own potential and ability to achieve sustainable development goals upon completing the service-learning projects

Students will have developed a general and comprehensive understanding of China’s cultural landscape, using the approach of cultural geography. Broad issues regarding China’s cultural heritages will be discussed to appreciate that cultural landscape formation is the result of multiple forces (e.g. natural, geographical, social, economic, political, etc) working together to form space and then places. After completing the course, students will have:

• identified essential features of Chinese cultural landscape;
• understood China’s multiple dimensions and geographical variations, and how these shape and reinforce space, place and cultural formation;
• discovered cases or used experiences to describe how the development of Chinese cultural landscape is associated with forces at different geographical scales such as local, regional, national and even global scales;
• explained their own ideas and critically engage in discussion in relation to cultural geography in China;
• diagnosed the political, social, economic and environmental dimensions of cultural landscape formation and transformation.
• obtained practical experience and undertake service-learning activities through purposely designed learning activities.

After completing this course, the students are expected to:
[1] understand the meaning of the terms and concepts of gene technology, human genome and genome projects, genetic engineering, synthetic biology, eugenics, bioethics;
[2] understand the diversity of genes in populations, recombinant DNA methods, concepts of genetic screening and gene therapy;
[3] understand the concepts of how genes affect our behaviours;
[4] understand what genetically modified foods are and their contributions;
[5] understand the uses and misuses of animal cloning;
[6] understand the potential uses of synthetic biology for making drugs and biofuels
[7] learn from specific cases which receive much attention of the ethical use of technologies in sports, reproduction and medicare research;
[8] understand the considerations and laws regulating fertilization, reproduction, and biosafety.

